\begin_layout Standard
In this experiment, we're going to shine a laser through the two nearby
 slits.
 We'll see a mix of interference and diffraction because the slits are much
 wider than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; there'll be the big center peak of diffraction modulated by the interference
 pattern and smaller peaks to the sides.
 See Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:data"

\end_inset

.
 The plan is to measure the pattern and determine the laser's wavelength
 from that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:double"

\end_inset

.
 We're working in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1},d_{2}\gg W$
\end_inset

.
 That makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}\approx\theta\approx\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

, so the two lines are roughly parallel.
 That means the blue side of the triangle, 
\begin_inset Formula $W\sin\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx d_{2}-d_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For constructive interference we still need that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|d_{2}-d_{1}\right|=n\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 That means 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n\lambda}{W}=\sin\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, which can further be approximated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n\lambda}{W}\approx\theta$
\end_inset

 since we'll be working with small 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, for destructive interference, we'll need 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)\lambda}{W}\approx\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a check, here's a quick derivation with the law of cosines and some Taylor
 expansion to show that it works out (similar to the derivation in lecture):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d_{1}^{2} & = & d_{2}^{2}+W^{2}-2d_{2}W\cos\left(\theta_{2}+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\\
 & = & d_{2}^{2}+W^{2}+2d_{2}W\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
 & \approx & d_{2}^{2}+2d_{2}W\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
d_{1} & = & d_{2}\sqrt{1+2\frac{W}{d_{2}}\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)}\\
 & \approx & d_{2}-W\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
d_{2}-d_{1} & = & W\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
 & \approx & W\sin\left(\theta\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That derivation may seem a little sketchy because we're approximating the
 angles to be the same, but we're not doing the same for the distances.
 That's because a tiny change in the distances can have a large effect,
 so I used a more accurate approximation for them.
 For example, red light has 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\approx680nm$
\end_inset

, so a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|d_{1}-d_{2}\right|$
\end_inset

 of only 
\begin_inset Formula $340nm$
\end_inset

 can get you from constructive to destructive interference -- from light
 to darkness.
\end_layout

